                <th>4</th>
                <td>
                  1. Area to be scanned using CAT and ground to be marked up
                  prior to any works commencing on site looking out for service
                  indicators above ground.<br />
                  2. Trace the service out of the dig area, marking the position
                  as required with spray paint.<br />
                  3. Ensure that the ground is well marked and all the crew
                  members fully understand all the ground markings, where all
                  buried services were located before excavation commences.<br
                  />
                  4. Place the Genny on the ground in line with the suspected
                  route of the target lines.<br />
                  5. Using the C.A.T away from the Genny, pinpoint the position
                  of the target line.<br />
                  6.Service drawings to be studied and locations which indicate
                  the presence of services to be checked against the CAT
                  identified markings. If services are shown on drawings but not
                  picked up by the scanner these areas indicated on the drawings
                  must be treatedas having potential services., until further
                  investigation proves otherwise.<br />
                  7.All indicators such as: ESB furniture, Gas furniture, street
                  furniture, water meters in residences should also be included
                  as part of the investigation of possible service locations.<br
                  />
                  8.Once all potential services located by the CAT and from
                  drawings and furniture indicators have been marked, the
                  location of the trial holes should be marked near any
                  potential service.<br />
                  9.The surface of these dig locations/trial holes, may be
                  broken mechanically or by hand.<br />
                  10. Using a road saw, cut the line of the trial hole.<br />
                  11. Once the surface is removed the excavation (trial hole) to
                  the potential Surface must be carried out by hand. No breaking
                  and/ or digging to take place directly over the service.<br />
                  12.Once physically located, these services will be identified
                  and exposed by hand digging. If service is proven in concrete
                  a switch out will be required. Never try to break/nibble in to
                  a service encased in concrete.<br />
                  13.When the surface is completely broken and removed trenching
                  may commence in the areas where no services were marked and
                  are 500mm away from the located services. Place a physical
                  item, such as: timber planks or a shovel near the service to
                  visually guide the excavator operator away from the service
                  and stop the bucket from damaging the service this should be
                  located approximately 500mm away. During the excavation check
                  for services, paying attention to any changes in the soil
                  type, colour and smell. Excavator driver to notify his
                  banksman if he feels any change in this controls. Banksman to
                  check the area.<br />
                  14. There is no way of confirming whether or not there is
                  service present in the area despite no signal being picked up
                  by the CAT or no drawings showing any services, so we must
                  treat them as having services.<br />
                  15.The trenching process should just take a scrape of the
                  surface in each run.<br />
                  16.This trenching process will be implemented between the
                  located service exclusion zones.<br />
                  17.When scraping the ground the banksman is to examine each
                  layer by scanning and hand digging regularly to check for the
                  presence of a services. paying attention to any changes in the
                  soil type, colour and smell. Once banksman is sure the layer
                  is clear the excavator driver can scrape away the layer.
                  Excavator driver to notify his banksman if he feels any change
                  in this controls. Banksman to check the area.<br />
                  18. Hand digging must be implemented within the located
                  services.<br />
                  19.The trenching process must be implemented for the full
                  depth of the excavation using safe systems of digging.
