                <td>
                  CAT must be certified for user Trained operator (CSCS
                  Certified) and LUGS training.<br />
                  Remember that services cables and public lights may not be
                  shown.<br />
                  Do not assume that CATs find buried utilities. They find
                  signals. Use the CAT in all models of operation to detect all
                  signals.<br />
                  Do not assume once a shallow cable or pipe is excavated that
                  this is the only utility there. Use the CAT and check to make
                  sure there are no additional buried utilities.<br />
                  Repeat the sweep process at regular depth intervals during the
                  excavation.<br />
                  Any identifled services using the CAT should be reflected in
                  the permit to dig. Completed permit daily.<br />
                  Sometimes it is not possible to define a zero and a maximum
                  signal over a buried service, particularly when it is
                  radiating a strong Power signal. Raise the C.A.T to 0.5 m from
                  the ground, reducing the sensitivity if necessary, then rotate
                  to find the minimum signal.<br />
                  Ensure that the ground is well marked where all buried
                  services were located before excavation commences.<br />
                  If the signal is lost, stop and locate in a circle 1 m around
                  the point where the signal was lost. The C.A.T gave a response
                  where the service entered the circle, and if the service has
                  curved, another response where it leaves the circle. If there
                  is no second response, increase the sensitivity to check if
                  the signal has divided into a tee or has weakened due to
                  increased depth. Trace the service back to a point where it
                  can be identified, i.e. valve, junction box, street lighting
                  column etc.<br />
                  Do not use hand held power tools directly over marked line of
                  cable UNLESS (a) You have already found the cable at that
                  position by careful hand digging beneath the surface AND it is
                  at a safe depth (at least 300mm) below the bottom of the
                  surface to be broken OR (b) Physical means have been used to
                  prevent the tool striking it.<br />
                  When the surface has been broken out, use Cable Locator again
                  to re-confirm the n position of services. Frequent and
                  repeated use should be made of CAT during the course of the
                  work.<br />
                  Do not handle or attempt to alter the position of exposed
                  electricity cables (unless under the direction of approved ESB
                  personnel).<br />
                  All personnel on site must implement the rules and guidelines
                  set out by the ESB regarding safe digging practice.<br />
                  Special care should be taken when digging above or close to
                  the assumed lines of any services. Every effort should be made
                  to excavate alongside the service rather than directly above
                  it. Final exposure of the service by horizontal digging is
                  recommended as the force applied to hand tools may be
                  controlled more effectively.<br />
                  Do not use hand held power tools within 0.5 metres of marked
                  position of electricity cables unless the no. of services
                  makes it impossible or surface obstructions reduce the space
                  available.
